AGI - US President Joe Biden spoke on the phone with Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu to discuss the latest developments in Israel and Gaza. The White House reports that the interview between the two leaders lasted less than 30 minutes.&nbsp; During the call, American media reports citing American administration sources, US President Joe Biden was described as "very angry" about the Israeli attack in which seven volunteers were working for World Central Kitchen. For Biden, attacks and the general humanitarian situation in Gaza are unacceptable. &nbsp;
&nbsp;
Biden explained "the need for Israel to announce and implement a series of specific, concrete and measurable measures to reduce civil damage, humanitarian suffering and the security of humanitarian workers". Biden explained that "the US policy towards Gaza will be determined by our assessment of Israel's immediate action on these measures." The President of the United States stressed that "an immediate ceasefire is essential to stabilise and improve the humanitarian situation and protect innocent civilians", and urged the Israeli Prime Minister "to give its negotiators the power to conclude an undoubted agreement to bring the hostages home."
&nbsp;
"We will hurt those who hurt us or who want to hurt us." Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu said this to a security cabinet meeting, immediately after his phone call with US President Joe Biden, referring to threats from Iran. "Iran has been acting against us for years - directly and through delegation. And, therefore, Israel acts against Iran and its delegates - defensively and offensively," he says. "We will defend ourselves and act according to the simple principle: those who hurt us or intend to hurt us, we will hurt," said the prime minister.
&nbsp;
Finally, chapter Iran. In the telephone interview Biden and Netanyahu discussed "the Iranian public threats against Israel and the Israeli people". President Biden clarified that the United States " strongly support Israel against these threats".
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
<h2>New vessel for aids
The Israeli government in time of war approved the opening of an important border crossing in northern Gaza while increasing pressure for the region to gain more critical access to humanitarian aid for the Palestinians in difficulty. The government - writes the American newspaper The Hill - will take immediate steps to open the Erez border crossing in northern Gaza, according to a statement of the Israeli Prime Minister's office shared by the Israeli media.
"This increase in aid will avoid a humanitarian crisis and it is necessary to ensure the continuation of the fights and to achieve the objectives of the war", we read in the statement. Erez's checkpoint will be the third open access point for the delivery of aid to Gaza after the Kerem Shalom pass in southern Israel and another bordering Egypt in the city of Rafah, where more than a million Palestinians are taking refuge from the war. According to the statement, the Israeli government will also increase the amount of "aid to Jordan through Kerem Shalom". Israeli National Security Minister Itamar Ben-Gvir said that the government in time of war did not approve the opening of a new vessel, according to a statement shared by Israeli media. Ben-Gvir, an extreme right-wing politician, opposed to sending more aid to Gaza, raising concerns for equipment that end up in the hands of Hamas.

<div </div

The White House National Security Council spokesman, Adrienne Watson, welcomed the steps of the Israeli government, stating that "they now need to be fully and quickly implemented." "As the President said today during the appeal, US policy on Gaza will be determined by our assessment of Israel's immediate action on these and other measures, including measures to protect innocent civilians and the security of humanitarian workers," said the White House. in a press release.&nbsp;
&nbsp;

