AGI - Since 1990, global average life expectancy has increased by 6.2 years, thanks to the best ability to deal with diseases such as enteric infections or respiratory tract, strokes and other conditions. These encouraging results emerge from a study, published in The Lancet, conducted by scientists from the Institute for Health Metrics and Evaluation (IHME). The team, led by Liane Ong, examined data on deaths occurring globally between 1990 and 2021. The research group has identified the main causes of death, highlighting the differences in life expectancy due to the best capacities of the health system to intervene in case of certain conditions.
&nbsp;
In 2020, experts observe, the Covid-19 pandemic significantly reduced life expectancy, in some locations more than in others. Despite the challenges presented by the coronavirus, between 1990 and 2021 many realities experienced a significant increase in life expectancy. In particular, between South-East Asia, East Asia and Oceania there is the highest absolute improvement found, equal to 8.3 years more than 30 years ago. “Our investigation – observes Ong – presents a blurred picture of world health. On the one hand, we see remarkable results in the prevention of deaths for strokes and diarrhoic diseases. At the same time, it is evident that pandemic caused an incredibly high number of losses in terms of human lives.”
&nbsp;
According to current estimates, Covid-19 was particularly lethal in Latin America, Caribbean and sub-Saharan Africa. Analyzing the different causes of death, the study showed a sharp drop in deaths for enteric diseases, such as diarrhea and typhus. These improvements have increased life expectancy across the world by 1.1 years over time. The treatment capabilities of lower respiratory infections added 0.9 years. Progress in preventing deaths associated with other disorders has significantly contributed to this value. Researchers also examined how disease models moved from one place to another over time.
&nbsp;
“Our knowledge of certain health conditions has increased considerably over the last 30 years – says Mohsen Naghavi, another signature of the article – we must focus on prevention and treatment of potentially lethal conditions for which we can develop effective care. We hope that our work will lead to an expansion of immunization programs and a more capillary distribution of existing vaccines.” “The global community – concludes Eve Wool, Senior Research Manager at IHME – must ensure that lifesaving tools, which in high-income countries have reduced the mortality rate associated with stroke, ischemic cardiopathy and other conditions, are available to people in all countries, even where resources are limited.” &nbsp;

